              </TimePeriod>
            </validTime>
          </tendency>
          <avActivityHighlights>The large quantity of fresh snow and in particular the widespread wind slabs can be released very easily.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>Above approximately 1000 m snow fell yesterday. As a consequence of new snow and a moderate to strong northeasterly wind, sometimes deep wind slabs formed in particular on southwest, south and southeast facing slopes. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; In particular sunny slopes as well as adjacent to ridgelines and in gullies and bowls: New snow and wind slabs are lying on a hard crust. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; The fresh and somewhat older wind slabs can be released by a single winter sport participant in all aspects and generally above the tree line. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; Careful route selection and spacing between individuals are recommended.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>In particular adjacent to ridgelines and in pass areas and high altitudes and the high Alpine regions: In the last four days hard wind slabs formed. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; In particular sunny slopes low and intermediate altitudes: The old snowpack is hard and its surface has a melt-freeze crust. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; In the areas described above, the new wind slabs will bond poorly with the old snowpack.</snowpackStructureComment>
        </BulletinMeasurements>
      </bulletinResultsOf>
